Fernhurst, Sussex, England":"Fernhurst, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1530–":"1530–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1552–Male":"1552–Deceased","1553–Female":"1553–Deceased","1530–Male":"1530–Deceased","29 Aug 1553  ":"29 August 1553","1553":"1553","1530":"1530","1552":"1552","Fernhurst, Sussex, England":"Fernhurst, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Yalden","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: variant of   Alden   (1), with the characteristically southern development of Middle English initial  <i>Ea-</i> to a rising diphthong, resulting in  <i>Y-</i>. Some of the post-medieval bearers cited here may belong to (2).","2  English: locative name from Yalding (Kent), which is recorded as  <i>Alding’</i> in 1161–2,  <i>Ealding’</i> in 1207,  <i>Yaldyng</i> in 1451. The place-name means ‘(settlement of) the people of a man called Ealda’, deriving from the Old English personal name  <i>Ealda</i> + the group-name suffix  <i>-ingas</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Alden","meanings":["English: from a Middle English personal name. This is either <i>Aldwin</i>, <i>Aldin</i> (representing Old English <i>Ealdwine</i> with loss of <i>-w-</i>) or Middle English <i>Alwin</i> with an intrusive <i>-d-</i> (see   Alwin  ), or <i>Aldan</i>, a variant of the Anglo-Scandinavian personal name <i>Healfdene</i> (see   Haldane  ).","Norwegian: habitational name from a farmstead in western Norway, so named because of its situation below a high mountain Alden, from an unattested word ‘high, standing out’.","History: John Alden (<i>c.</i> 1599–1687) was one of the Pilgrim Fathers who sailed on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1620. He moved from Plymouth to Duxbury, MA, <i>c.</i> 1627. Many of his descendants were merchant seamen, among them James Alden (1810–77), who twice circumnavigated the globe."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Yalden was born in 1530, in Fernhurst, Sussex, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with ?."},"et":{"1530–":"1530–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1552–Male":"1552–Surnud","1553–Female":"1553–Surnud","1530–Male":"1530–Surnud","29 Aug 1553  ":"29. august 1553","1553":"1553","1530":"1530","1552":"1552","Fernhurst, Sussex, England":"Fernhurst, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1530–":"1530–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1552–Male":"1552–Kuollut","1553–Female":"1553–Kuollut","1530–Male":"1530–Kuollut","29 Aug 1553  ":"29. elokuuta 1553","1553":"1553","1530":"1530","1552":"1552","Fernhurst, Sussex, England":"Fernhurst, Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1530–":"1530–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1552–Male":"1552–Décédé","1553–Female":"1553–Décédée","1530–Male":"1530–Décédé","29 Aug 1553  ":"29 août 1553","1553":"1553","1530":"1530","1552":"1552","Fernhurst, Sussex, England":"Fernhurst, Sussex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"William Yalden est né en 1530, à Fernhurst, Sussex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec ?."},"de":{"1530–":"1530–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1552–Male":"1552–Verstorben","1553–Female":"1553–Verstorben","1530–Male":"1530–Verstorben","29 Aug 1553  ":"29. August 15